[Far be it from me to cave in to the voices of reason. Doesn't matter to
me that other Moderators are willing to use the term "epidemic" (Greek: epi
= among, upon + demos = people) when they should be using "epizootic".
Another Moderator uses "epidemic" for the human half of an epizoodemic and
"epizootic" for the nonhuman half; fair enough. Quite apart from this
interesting case report (ibid), the question arises as to whether to use
the term "endemic" or "enzootic". Perfect example of people digging
themselves into a hole and then asking for help getting out. C-CHF virus
certainly is not endemic (continuously present among humans in a certain
region, a la cholera in some places). That C-CHF is enzootic in certain
regions is a certainty, although it must be noted that C-CHF virus
ordinarily cycles in ticks and small vertebrates and once in a while spills
over to larger vertebrates (cattle, humans). Please don't send me any more
messages trying to convince me to get with the program and use "epidemic"
when "epizootic" is correct. I haven't yet accepted the designated hitter,
and likely won't. - Mod.CHC
......................................chc/es
